   271	Notes on shape choices:
   272	
   273	- `name: eden-reference` is the project name. `compose up`,
   274	  `compose down`, and `compose ps` use this; without it the project
   275	  defaults to the directory name (`compose`) which is uselessly
   276	  generic.
   277	- `${VAR:?msg}` syntax for required secrets means `compose up`
   278	  fails fast with a clear message if the user hasn't copied
   279	  `.env.example` to `.env`. `${VAR:-default}` for optional values.
   280	- Port collisions on the host are likely (a developer probably has
   281	  Postgres 5432 in use; some have Gitea 3000). Defaulting host-side
   282	  to 5433 / 3001 / 2222 sidesteps the most common collisions.
   283	- `GITEA__security__INSTALL_LOCK: "true"` — skip the first-run
   284	  installer wizard. With `INSTALL_LOCK=true` plus
   285	  `DISABLE_REGISTRATION=true`, Gitea boots straight into headless
   286	  mode. Admin user creation happens in 10c.
   287	- The blob volume is declared at the top level and mounted by the
   288	  one-shot `blob-init` service so Compose actually creates it at
   289	  `compose up` (an unmounted declaration alone does not, per the
   290	  empirical spike noted in Core Design Decisions). Downstream
   291	  services in 10b/10d mount the same volume at `/var/lib/eden/blobs`.
   292	  `--wait` exits 0 when `blob-init` exits 0; the smoke test re-checks
   293	  via `docker volume inspect`.
   294	- No `networks:` block: services land on Compose's default
   295	  bridge network. Service discovery via container name
   296	  (`postgres:5432`, `gitea:3000`) just works; explicit network
   297	  declarations matter for multi-stack overlap, which 10a doesn't
   298	  have.
