   348	### `reference/compose/healthcheck/smoke.sh`
   349	
   350	Bash script, exits 0 on success. Used by the new CI job and runnable
   351	locally for verification. Behavior:
   352	
   353	```bash
   354	#!/usr/bin/env bash
   355	set -euo pipefail
   356	
   357	# Bring the stack up using .env.example as the source of truth.
   358	# (Copy to a temp .env if invoked from CI to avoid mutating the
   359	# checked-in file.)
   360	TMPENV="$(mktemp)"
   361	trap 'rm -f "$TMPENV"; docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" down -v' EXIT
   362	cp .env.example "$TMPENV"
   363	
   364	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" up -d --wait --wait-timeout 120
   365	
   366	# Assert both long-running services are healthy.
   367	# `--wait` already enforces this, but we re-check for clarity in CI logs.
   368	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" ps
   369	
   370	# Assert all three named volumes were created at compose-up time.
   371	# blob-init mounts eden-blob-data so Compose creates it; postgres and
   372	# gitea mount their own data volumes the usual way. Project-prefixed
   373	# volume names follow the "<project>_<volume>" convention; the project
   374	# name is fixed by `name: eden-reference` in compose.yaml and is also
   375	# echoed below for traceability.
   376	PROJECT="$(docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" \
   377	            config --format json | jq -r '.name')"
   378	test "$PROJECT" = "eden-reference" \
   379	    || { echo "unexpected project name: $PROJECT"; exit 1; }
   380	for vol in eden-postgres-data eden-gitea-data eden-blob-data; do
   381	    docker volume inspect "${PROJECT}_${vol}" >/dev/null
   382	done
   383	
   384	# Confirm blob-init actually exited 0 (--wait would have failed
   385	# otherwise, but re-checking gives a useful CI log line).
   386	test "$(docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" \
   387	        ps -a --format json blob-init | jq -r '.ExitCode')" = "0"
   388	
   389	# Assert Postgres is accepting connections (independent of healthcheck).
   390	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" exec -T postgres \
   391	    pg_isready -U eden -d eden
   392	
   393	# Assert Gitea API responds.
   394	GITEA_PORT="$(grep ^GITEA_HOST_PORT "$TMPENV" | cut -d= -f2)"
   395	curl -fsS "http://localhost:${GITEA_PORT}/api/v1/version" | grep -q '"version":'
   396	
   397	echo "PASS"
   398	```
   399	
   400	Notes:
   401	
   402	- The `trap` ensures teardown runs even on assertion failure, so
   403	  CI runs don't leave dangling volumes.
   404	- `--wait --wait-timeout 120` (Compose v2 feature) makes `up`
   405	  block until every service is healthy or 2min elapses, exiting
   406	  non-zero if any service fails. This is the cleanest way to
   407	  encode "everything came up healthy" in a script.
   408	- The volume name is the standard `<project>_<volume>` Compose
   409	  convention. The script reads the project name from
   410	  `docker compose config` and asserts it equals
   411	  `eden-reference` (matching the `name:` field in `compose.yaml`)
   412	  before applying the prefix, so a future rename of `name:`
   413	  fails the smoke test loudly rather than silently checking
   414	  the wrong volumes.
