     1	# EDEN Phase 10 chunk 10a: Compose Infrastructure
     2	
     3	## Context
     4	
     5	Phase 9 closed with a complete Web UI: a human can play any role
     6	end-to-end through a browser, and `/admin/*` exposes observability and
     7	operator-reclaim. Every service is currently run as a Python module
     8	(`python -m eden_task_store_server …`, etc.) against ephemeral
     9	SQLite + a local bare git repo.
    10	
    11	Phase 10 packages the reference stack so it runs locally via
    12	`docker compose up`. Per the roadmap, the phase splits into five
    13	chunks; this plan covers **chunk 10a**:
    14	
    15	> **10a** — Infrastructure containers (Postgres for durable backend,
    16	> Gitea for git host, blob volume) + Compose skeleton that stands them
    17	> up.
    18	
    19	Subsequent chunks will dockerize the EDEN services themselves (10b),
    20	add the experiment-registration script (10c), wire LLM workers (10d),
    21	and ship the end-to-end Compose integration test (10e).
    22	
    23	**Critical scope clarification.** 10a is *only* the infrastructure
    24	layer: third-party stateful services (Postgres, Gitea), the named
    25	volume that will eventually back blob storage, and the Compose file
    26	that stands them up. **No EDEN services are dockerized in 10a.** No
    27	new Python code in `reference/packages/` or `reference/services/`.
    28	No `PostgresStore` implementation — `eden-storage` already ships
    29	`SqliteStore` and `InMemoryStore`; the Postgres binding lands when a
    30	consumer exists (10b alongside the dockerized `task-store-server`).
    31	The blob package (`reference/packages/eden-blob/`) stays a `.gitkeep`
    32	until 10d when the implementer host needs to publish artifacts.
    33	
    34	**Postgres is for the EDEN task store, not for Gitea.** The roadmap
    35	phrases 10a's deliverables as "Postgres for durable backend, Gitea
    36	for git host," which scoped together can read as "Postgres backs
    37	Gitea." It does not. Gitea ships with its own embedded SQLite and
    38	that's what the 10a Compose file uses (`GITEA__database__DB_TYPE:
    39	sqlite3`). Pointing Gitea at our Postgres would couple the git
    40	host's recovery story to EDEN's task store schema — something a
    41	reference deployment of EDEN should explicitly not do, since
    42	production deployments should be free to swap either component
    43	independently. The Postgres container in 10a is reserved for
    44	`PostgresStore` consumption in 10b.
    45	
    46	Why ship infra without consumers? Three reasons:
    47	
    48	1. **Image-pin & config-shape stability lands first.** Pinning
    49	   image tags, naming volumes, choosing the postgres user/db scheme,
    50	   and picking the Gitea admin bootstrap pattern are all decisions
    51	   that downstream chunks consume. Surfacing them now means 10b/10c/10d
    52	   only have to write app code, not also negotiate infra shape.
    53	2. **Smoke-testable in isolation.** A standalone Compose file with
    54	   healthchecks can be brought up in CI with no EDEN dependencies,
    55	   so Compose drift is caught even when the python suite is green.
    56	3. **Chunk discipline.** The roadmap explicitly groups 10b + 10c into
    57	   one chunk and lists 10a separately. Co-mingling 10a with backend
    58	   bindings violates that grouping.
    59	
    60	## Core Design Decisions
    61	
    62	- **`reference/compose/` is the home for everything.** Compose file,
    63	  `.env.example`, init scripts, README. No top-level `docker-compose.yml`
    64	  at the repo root — that would imply the whole repo is "a docker
    65	  thing," which it isn't.
    66	- **One Compose file, no overrides yet.** A single
    67	  `compose.yaml` in 10a. Profile-based service splits
    68	  (`compose --profile workers`) are tempting but premature; 10b will
    69	  add EDEN services to the same file, and 10e may add an override
    70	  for the e2e test. Adding a second file now would force us to move
    71	  things around in 10b.
    72	- **Image tags pinned to specific minor versions, never `:latest`.**
    73	  Selected versions:
    74	  - `postgres:16.6-alpine` — current Postgres stable, alpine variant
    75	    keeps the image small. Postgres 16 is the line direvo's monolith
    76	    targeted; staying on it minimizes surprises when Phase 10b adds
    77	    `PostgresStore`.
    78	  - `gitea/gitea:1.22.6-rootless` — current Gitea stable, rootless
    79	    variant runs as uid 1000 instead of root (Gitea publishes both
    80	    flavors and explicitly recommends rootless for new deployments).
    81	- **Default ports are off the well-known channels** (Postgres on 5433,
    82	  Gitea on 3001) so a developer's existing local Postgres / Gitea
    83	  doesn't collide. Documented in `.env.example`. Real production
    84	  deployments override.
    85	- **Secrets via `.env` only.** No secrets baked into the Compose file.
    86	  `.env.example` ships canned dev defaults; the real `.env` is
    87	  gitignored. CI uses `.env.example` as-is — these are throwaway
    88	  values, not real credentials.
    89	- **Healthchecks on every infra service.** Compose `depends_on`
    90	  semantics with `condition: service_healthy` are the only safe way
    91	  to chain bring-up; without healthchecks, "up" means "container
    92	  process started," not "Postgres is accepting connections." Each
    93	  service in 10a defines a `healthcheck:` block and downstream
    94	  services in 10b will gate on `service_healthy` instead of bare
    95	  `service_started`.
    96	- **Volume strategy — named volumes, not bind mounts.** Named volumes
    97	  (`eden-postgres-data`, `eden-gitea-data`, `eden-blob-data`) are
    98	  Compose-managed, survive `compose down` (use `compose down -v` to
    99	  wipe), and don't pollute the repo with `_data/` directories. Bind
   100	  mounts work but tie data location to the developer's filesystem
   101	  layout, which gets fragile when CI lays things out differently.
   102	- **Postgres bootstrap via `/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/`.** The
   103	  official Postgres image runs every `*.sql` and `*.sh` in that
   104	  directory the *first* time the data volume is empty. We ship one
   105	  init SQL file: `01-create-eden-db.sql`, which creates the `eden`
   106	  database and the `eden` role with an env-var-driven password.
   107	  (`POSTGRES_DB=eden` + `POSTGRES_USER=eden` + `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=…`
   108	  in `.env` is the simpler path and we use that — the init SQL is
   109	  needed only if we want extensions or extra roles. **Decision:**
   110	  use env-var bootstrap, **no init SQL file** in 10a. If a later
   111	  chunk needs `pg_stat_statements` or a second role we add init SQL
   112	  then. Keeps 10a smaller.)
   113	- **Gitea bootstrap via env vars.** Gitea respects `GITEA__<section>__<key>`
   114	  env vars at startup. We set the minimum needed for headless
   115	  operation: install lock skipped, no telemetry, JWT secret pinned
   116	  via `.env`, admin user *not* auto-created in 10a — 10c's
   117	  `setup-experiment` script will create the admin via the API or
   118	  `gitea admin user create` once there's a real consumer. (Creating
   119	  an admin in 10a means we'd have to choose a token-issuing scheme
   120	  before we have anything to issue tokens for.)
   121	- **Blob volume = named volume + one-shot `blob-init` mounter.**
   122	  Empirical Compose behavior verified during planning: a
   123	  top-level `volumes:` declaration **does not** cause Compose to
   124	  create the volume unless at least one service mounts it. A
   125	  bare declaration (no mount, no init service) leaves
   126	  `docker volume ls` empty after `compose up`. To make 10a's
   127	  deliverable real, we ship a one-shot `blob-init` busybox
   128	  container that mounts `eden-blob-data` at `/var/lib/eden/blobs`,
   129	  runs `mkdir -p`, and exits 0. `restart: "no"` prevents the
   130	  exited container from looping; `docker compose up --wait`
   131	  semantics for one-shot services were also verified during
   132	  planning — `--wait` returns exit 0 when a one-shot container
   133	  exits 0, so the smoke test gets a clean signal. Downstream
   134	  services in 10b/10d mount the same volume.
   135	- **10a's blob-volume guarantee is "volume exists," not
   136	  "writable by the eventual 10d producer."** `blob-init` runs as
   137	  BusyBox root, and any in-container writability check 10a runs
   138	  is also from a root container — that proves "root can write,"
   139	  which is uninformative for the eventual non-root LLM-worker
   140	  containers in 10d. We deliberately do **not** make a
   141	  uid/gid/perm contract in 10a. 10d picks the user model when
   142	  the first real producer lands and is responsible for any
   143	  ownership/`chmod`/`chown` step it needs. 10a's smoke test
   144	  asserts existence (`docker volume inspect`) and that the
   145	  `blob-init` container exited 0 — nothing more about the volume.
   146	- **Compose file format = `compose.yaml` (no `version:` field).**
   147	  Modern Docker Compose deprecated the top-level `version:` key and
   148	  Docker recommends using just `compose.yaml`. We name the file
   149	  `compose.yaml` (not `docker-compose.yml`) and omit `version:`.
   150	  `docker compose` (v2 plugin, the only supported flavor) accepts
   151	  both filenames; users on extremely old `docker-compose` (v1, EOL)
   152	  may be surprised, and that's an acceptable cost — v1 has been
   153	  unmaintained for 18+ months.
   154	
   155	## What Gets Created
   156	
   157	```text
   158	reference/compose/
   159	├── README.md                 # How to bring it up + what each service does + ops notes
   160	├── compose.yaml              # The Compose file. Three services + three volumes.
   161	├── .env.example              # Default env values; gitignored ".env" is the real file.
   162	└── healthcheck/
   163	    └── smoke.sh              # Bash script: bring up, wait for healthy, assert volume,
   164	                              # tear down. Used by both the human verification step
   165	                              # and the new compose-smoke CI job.
   166	
   167	.github/workflows/ci.yml      # New job: compose-smoke
   168	.gitignore                    # Add: reference/compose/.env
   169	docs/roadmap.md               # Mark 10a complete
   170	reference/README.md           # Update Compose row from "Phase 10" → "Phase 10 chunk 10a"
   171	AGENTS.md                     # Append Phase 10 chunk 10a paragraph
   172	```
   173	
   174	**Not** created in 10a:
   175	
   176	- Any Dockerfile under `reference/services/*/` — those land in 10b.
   177	- Any `PostgresStore` code in `reference/packages/eden-storage/` —
   178	  defers until 10b ships the consumer.
   179	- `reference/packages/eden-blob/*.py` — defers to 10d.
   180	- `reference/scripts/setup-experiment/` content — that's 10c.
   181	- A repo-root `compose.yaml` — only `reference/compose/compose.yaml`.
   182	
   183	## File-by-file design
   184	
   185	### `reference/compose/compose.yaml`
   186	
   187	Three services and three named volumes. `postgres` and `gitea`
   188	mount their own data volumes; `blob-init` is a one-shot service
   189	whose only purpose is to ensure `eden-blob-data` is created.
   190	
   191	```yaml
   192	name: eden-reference
   193	
   194	services:
   195	  postgres:
   196	    image: postgres:16.6-alpine
   197	    container_name: eden-postgres
   198	    restart: unless-stopped
   199	    environment:
   200	      POSTGRES_DB: ${POSTGRES_DB:-eden}
   201	      POSTGRES_USER: ${POSTGRES_USER:-eden}
   202	      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD:?POSTGRES_PASSWORD must be set}
   203	    ports:
   204	      - "${POSTGRES_HOST_PORT:-5433}:5432"
   205	    volumes:
   206	      - eden-postgres-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data
   207	    healthcheck:
   208	      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U ${POSTGRES_USER:-eden} -d ${POSTGRES_DB:-eden}"]
   209	      interval: 5s
   210	      timeout: 3s
   211	      retries: 10
   212	      start_period: 10s
   213	
   214	  gitea:
   215	    image: gitea/gitea:1.22.6-rootless
   216	    container_name: eden-gitea
   217	    restart: unless-stopped
   218	    environment:
   219	      GITEA__server__DOMAIN: localhost
   220	      GITEA__server__ROOT_URL: http://localhost:${GITEA_HOST_PORT:-3001}/
   221	      GITEA__server__HTTP_PORT: "3000"
   222	      # SSH_PORT is the *advertised* port (shown in clone URLs); it must
   223	      # match the host-side mapping so SSH clones work. SSH_LISTEN_PORT
   224	      # is what Gitea binds inside the container, kept fixed at 2222
   225	      # so the published mapping below stays valid even when a user
   226	      # overrides GITEA_SSH_HOST_PORT to dodge a host collision.
   227	      GITEA__server__SSH_PORT: "${GITEA_SSH_HOST_PORT:-2222}"
   228	      GITEA__server__SSH_LISTEN_PORT: "2222"
   229	      GITEA__database__DB_TYPE: sqlite3
   230	      GITEA__database__PATH: /var/lib/gitea/data/gitea.db
   231	      GITEA__security__INSTALL_LOCK: "true"
   232	      GITEA__security__SECRET_KEY: ${GITEA_SECRET_KEY:?GITEA_SECRET_KEY must be set}
   233	      GITEA__security__INTERNAL_TOKEN: ${GITEA_INTERNAL_TOKEN:?GITEA_INTERNAL_TOKEN must be set}
   234	      GITEA__service__DISABLE_REGISTRATION: "true"
   235	      GITEA__metrics__ENABLED: "false"
   236	      GITEA__log__LEVEL: Warn
   237	    ports:
   238	      - "${GITEA_HOST_PORT:-3001}:3000"
   239	      - "${GITEA_SSH_HOST_PORT:-2222}:2222"
   240	    volumes:

